pe               = Admin HQ.\n| seat                    = [[Khalanga, Mahakali]] (today part of [[Mahakali, Darchula|Mahakali Municipality]]) \n| leader_title            = Head\n| leader_name             = Mr. Karbir Singh Karki\n| leader_party            = \n| leader_title1           = Deputy-Head\n| leader_name1            = Mr. Krishna Singh Dhami\n| leader_title2           = [[House of Representatives (Nepal)|Parliamentary constituencies]]\n| leader_name2            = 1\n\n| leader_title3           = [[Provincial Assembly (Nepal)|Provincial constituencies]]\n| leader_name3            = 2\n| government_footnotes    = \n| government_type         = [[District Coordination Committee|Coordination committee]]\n| governing_body          = [[District Coordination Committee|DCC]], Darchula \n| area_footnotes          = \n| area_total_km2          = 2322\n| area_note               = \n| area_rank               = \n| elevation_footnotes     = \n| elevation_m             = \n| elevation_min_m         = 518\n| elevation_max_m         = 7132\n| population_footnotes    =<ref name=\"National Population and Housing Census 2011(National Report)\">{{cite news|title=National Population and Housing Census 2011(National Report) |url=http://cbs.gov.np/wp-content/uploads/2012/11/National%20Report.pdf |accessdate=1 November 2012 |agency=Government of Nepal |publisher=[[Central Bureau of Statistics (Nepal)|Central Bureau of Statistics]] |date=November 2012 |ref=Central Bureau of Statistics |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130418000000/http://cbs.gov.np/wp-content/uploads/2012/11/National%20Report.pdf |archivedate=18 April 2013 }}</ref>\n| population_total        = 133274\n| population_as_of        = 2011\n| population_density_km2  = 57\n| population_note         = \n| population_rank         = \n\n| blank_name_sec1         = [[Languages of Nepal|Main Language(s)]]\n| blank_info_sec1         = [[Doti]]yali, [[Kumaoni language|Kumauni]], [[Rung languages|Rung/Shauka]], [[Nepali language|Nepali]] and others{{citation needed|date=September 2018}}\n| blank_name_sec2         = [[Roads in Nepal|Major highways]]\n| blank_info_sec2         = \n\n| timezone1               = [[Nepal Time|NPT]]\n| utc_offset1             = +05:45\n| postal_code_type        = Postal Codes\n| postal_code             = \n| area_code_type          = Telephone Code\n| area_code               = \n| website                 = {{URL|ddcdarchula.gov.np}}\n| footnotes               = \n}}\n\n'''Darchula District''' ({{lang-ne|[[:ne:\u0926\u093e\u0930\u094d\u091a\u0941\u0932\u093e \u091c\u093f\u0932\u094d\u0932\u093e|\u0926\u093e\u0930\u094d\u091a\u0941\u0932\u093e \u091c\u093f\u0932\u094d\u0932\u093e]]}} {{Audio|Darchula.ogg|Listen}}, a part of [[Sudurpashchim Pradesh]], is one of the nine districts of province and one of seventy-seven [[Districts of Nepal|districts]] of [[Nepal]]. The district, with [[Khalanga, Mahakali]] (today part of [[Mahakali, Darchula|Mahakali Municipality]]) as its district headquarters, covers an area of {{cvt|2,322|km2}} and has a population (2011) of 133,274.<ref name=\"National Population and Housing Census 2011(National Report)\" /> Darchula Lies in the west-north corner of the country.\n\n==Etymology==\nDarchula is made of two words \"Dar\" (ne:\u0926\u093e\u0930) and \"Chula\" (ne:\u091a\u0941\u0932\u093e). Dar means edge (peak) in Nepali and Chula means fire stove, literally meaning a fire stove made of three stones (or peaks of three hills/mountains). Almost all people in this place used to cook on a fire stove made of three stones. Also, there are mountain peaks here which look like a three-stone fire stove. The legend says that sage [[Vyasa]] cooked his food here on a fire stove of three peaks.<ref>{{cite web \n|url=http://ddcdarchula.gov.np/ne-brief-introduction/ \n|title = \u0926\u093e\u0930\u094d\u091a\u0941\u0932\u093e \u091c\u093f\u0932\u094d\u0932\u093e\u0915\u094b \u0938\u0902\u0915\u094d\u0937\u093f\u092a\u094d\u0924 \u092a\u0930\u093f\u091a\u092f\n|date= \nn.d.|website= ddcdarchula.gov.np\n|publisher= DDC Darchula\n|access-date= 11 February 2020\n|language= Nepali\n}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nDarchula was a part of [[Doti]] Kingdom during the medieval era.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.volunteersummernepal.org/tag/deuki-pratha |title=Deuki Pratha |date=15 January 2012 |website= |access-date=18 February 2020}}</ref> Nepal annexed Doti in 1790<ref>{{cite web |url=http://epopee.huma-num.fr/epic_documents_MG_Bharats.htm |title=M. Gaborieau on 7 Bharats recorded in Nepal (1969) |date= n.d.|website= |access-date=18 February 2020}}</ref> and made it part of [[Doti District]] until 1885. After 1885 it became part of [[Baitadi District]]. [[Baitadi District|Baitadi]] and [[Dadeldhura District|Dadeldhura]] had same \"Bada-Hakim\" (District Administrators) so Those two districts jointly used to call '''Baitadi-Dadeldhura''' district. The \"Baitadi-Dadeldhura\" district named '''Mahakali District''' after 1956. In 1956 four county (Thums) of Baitadi separated and made a sub-district of Mahakali district. From 1956 to 1962 \"Mahakali district\" had three sub-districts.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://himalaya.socanth.cam.ac.uk/collections/rarebooks/downloads/Nepal_1948_Government_Act_English.pdf |title=Government of Nepal Act 1948}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= http://saruwa.moga.gov.np/mogawebsite/images/pdf/pratibedan/%E0%A4%AA%E0%A5%8D%E0%A4%B0%E0%A4%B6%E0%A4%BE%E0%A4%B8%E0%A4%95%E0%A5%80%E0%A4%AF%20%E0%A4%AA%E0%A5%81%E0%A4%A8%E0%A4%B0%E0%A5%8D%E0%A4%97%E0%A4%A0%E0%A4%A8%20%E0%A4%B8%E0%A4%AE%E0%A4%BF%E0%A4%A4%E0%A4%BF%20%28%E0%A4%AC%E0%A5%81%E0%A4%9A%20%E0%A4%95%E0%A4%AE%E0%A4%BF%E0%A4%B6%E0%A4%A8%29%20%E0%A4%95%E0%A5%8B%20%E0%A4%AA%E0%A5%8D%E0%A4%B0%E0%A4%A4%E0%A4%BF%E0%A4%B5%E0%A5%87%E0%A4%A6%E0%A4%A8,%20%E0%A5%A8%E0%A5%A6%E0%A5%A6%E0%A5%AF%20.pdf |title= \u092a\u094d\u0930\u0936\u093e\u0938\u0915\u0940\u092f \u092a\u0941\u0928\u0930\u094d\u0917\u0920\u0928 \u0938\u092e\u093f\u0924\u093f (\u092c\u0941\u091a \u0915\u092e\u093f\u0936\u0928) \u0915\u094b \u092a\u094d\u0930\u0924\u093f\u0935\u0947\u0926\u0928, \u0968\u0966\u0966\u096f }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= http://saruwa.moga.gov.np/mogawebsite/images/pdf/pratibedan/%E0%A4%A8%E0%A5%87%E0%A4%AA%E0%A4%BE%E0%A4%B2%E0%A4%95%E0%A5%8B%20%E0%A4%9C%E0%A4%BF%E0%A4%B2%E0%A5%8D%E0%A4%B2%E0%A4%BE%20%E0%A4%AA%E0%A5%8D%E0%A4%B0%E0%A4%B6%E0%A4%BE%E0%A4%B8%E0%A4%A8%20%E0%A4%AA%E0%A5%81%E0%A4%A8%E0%A4%B0%E0%A5%8D%E0%A4%97%E0%A4%A0%E0%A4%A8%E0%A4%95%E0%A5%8B%20%E0%A4%B0%E0%A4%BF%E0%A4%AA%E0%A5%8B%E0%A4%B0%E0%A5%8D%E0%A4%9F,%20%E0%A5%A8%E0%A5%A6%E0%A5%A7%E0%A5%A9.pdf |title= \u0928\u0947\u092a\u093e\u0932\u0915\u094b \u091c\u093f\u0932\u094d\u0932\u093e \u092a\u094d\u0930\u0936\u093e\u0938\u0928 \u092a\u0941\u0928\u0930\u094d\u0917\u0920\u0928\u0915\u094b \u0930\u093f\u092a\u094b\u0930\u094d\u091f, \u0968\u0966\u0967\u0969}}</ref>\n# Dadeldhura\n# Baitadi\n# Chamba\n\nIn 1962, Chamba separately upgraded to a district and named \"Darchula District\".\n{{Gallery\n| title        = District in different time\n| align        = \n| footer       =\n| style        =\n| state        =\n| height       =\n| width        =\n| captionstyle =\n| File:Baitadi-dadeldhura.png\n | alt1=\n | Darchula as a part of Baitadi sub-district of Mahakali (Baitadi-Dadeldhura) district (before 1956)\n| File:Baitadi-dadeldhura2.png\n | alt2=\n | Darchula (Chamba), a sub-district of Mahakali district (1956\u20131962)\n}}\n\n==Geography and climate==\nThe district is surrounded by [[Bajhang District]] in the east, [[Baitadi District]] in the east and the south, [[Ngari Prefecture]] of [[Tibet Autonomous Region|TAR]] of China in the North and [[Pithoragarh district]] of [[India]] in the West.\n\nThe [[Himalayas|Himalayan]] region between two rivers [[Sharda River|Kali River]] to [[Seti River]] calls [[Gurans Himal]].<ref>{{cite web \n|url=https://www.yetitrailadventure.com/nepal/himalaya.htmlb  \n|title = Himalaya\n|date= \nn.d.|website= yetitrailadventure.com\n|access-date= 11 February 2020\n}}</ref> Darchula district falls in the [[Gurans Himal]] zone. [[Api (mountain)|Api Himal]] ({{convert|7132|m|ft}}) and [[Jethi Bahurani]] ({{convert|6850|m|ft}}) are main mountain peaks of the area. There is a protected area named [[Api Nampa Conservation Area]] which ranges in elevation from {{convert|532|m|ft}} to {{convert|7132|m|ft}}. [[Mahakali river|Mahakali]], Chalune, Tinkar, Nampa and Kalagad are the rivers in the area.\n\nThe climate of the area is generally characterized by high rainfall and humidity. The climatic condition varies along with the elevation gradient. The climate of Darchula District varies widely from subtropical to alpine. In the north, most of the parts, having an alpine climate, remain under snow. In the southern part and valleys, the climate is subtropical. Mid- hills have a temperate climate. The average maximum temperature is 18.6&nbsp;\u00b0C and the minimum temperature is 7.7&nbsp;\u00b0C. The average rainfall is 2129mm. Most precipitation falls between May and September.\nAbout eighty percent of the total annual rainfall occurs during the monsoon season (June to September). All areas experience very high rainfall intensities, ranging between estimates of {{cvt|125|\u2013|350|mm}} for a 24-hour period.\nWithin its elevation range of {{cvt|1800|m}} to {{cvt|6500|m}}, there are limited subtropical valleys in the southern margin although most of the area is ecologically temperate or highland. A cold, generally dry climate exists in the high alpine valleys just north of the southern arm of the Himalayan mountain range which cuts across the bottom of Darchula.{{citation needed|date=September 2018}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! [[Geography of Nepal#Climate|Climate Zone]]<ref>\n{{Citation\n | author-link = Lilles\u00f8, J-P.B., T.B. Shrestha, L.P. Dhakal, R.P. Nayaju and R. Shrestha\n | title = The Map of Potential Vegetation of Nepal \u2013 a forestry/agroecological/biodiversity classification system\n | series = Forest & Landscape Development and Environment Series 2-2005 and CFC-TIS Document Series No.110. \n | year = 2005\n | url = http://curis.ku.dk/ws/files/20497354/de2_001.pdf\n | isbn = 87-7903-210-9\n | accessdate = 22 November 2013}}\n</ref>\n! Elevation Range\n! % of Area\n|-\n| Upper [[Tropical climate|Tropical]]\n| 300 to 1,000 meters<br>1,000 to 3,300&nbsp;ft.\n| &nbsp;4.7%\n|-\n| [[Subtropics|Subtropical]]\n| 1,000 to 2,000 meters<br>3,300 to 6,600&nbsp;ft.\n| 19.8%\n|-\n| [[Temperate climate|Temperate]]\n| 2,000 to 3,000 meters<br>6,400 to 9,800&nbsp;ft.\n| 22.2%\n|-\n| [[Montane ecology#Subalpine zone|Subalpine]]\n| 3,000 to 4,000 meters<br>9,800 to 13,100&nbsp;ft.\n| 20.5%\n|-\n| [[Montane ecology#Alpine grasslands and tundra|Alpine]]\n| 4,000 to 5,000 meters<br>13,100 to 16,400&nbsp;ft.\n|  15.3%\n|-\n| [[Snow line|Nival]]\n| above 5,000 meters\n|  17.5%\n|}\n{{clear}}\n===Major rivers===\n*[[Mahakali]]\n*Chalaune\n*[[Tinkar]]\n*Nampa\n*Kalagad\n\n==Administration==\nDarchula District is administered by [[District Coordination Committee|Darchula District Coordination Committee]] (Darchula DCC). The Darchula DCC is elected by [[Jilla Sabha|Darchula District Assembly]]. The head of Darchula DCC is Mr. Karbir Singh Karki and Mr. Krishna Singh Dhami is deputy head of Darchula DCC.\n\n[[District Administration in Nepal|Darchula District Administration Office]] under [[Ministry of Home Affairs (Nepal)|Ministry of Home Affairs]] co-operate with Darchula DCC to maintain peace, order and security in the district. The officer of District Administration office called [[Chief District Officer|CDO]] and current CDO of Darchula DAO is Yadunath Paudel\n\nDarchula District Court is a [[Judicial court]] to see the cases of people on district level.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Administration !! Name !! Head !! Website\n|-\n| Legislative||District Coordination Committee || Mr. Karbir Singh Karki || {{website|ddcdarchula.gov.np}}\n|-\n| Executive||District Administration Office || Mr. Yadunath Paudel || {{website|daodarchula.moha.gov.np}}\n|-\n| Judicial||District Court || Mr. Giriraj Gautam ||{{website|supremecourt.gov.np/court/darchuladc}}\n|}\n\n==Division==\nThe district consists of nine [[List of cities in Nepal|municipalities]], out of which two are urban municipalities and seven are [[Gaupalika|rural municipalities]]. These are as follows:<ref>{{cite web |title=\u0938\u094d\u0925\u093e\u0928\u093f\u092f \u0924\u0939 |url=http://103.69.124.141/ |publisher=Ministry of Federal Affairs and General Administration |accessdate=1 September 2018 |language=Nepali}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! SN !! Local level unit!! Type !! Population !! Area !! No. of wards !! Website\n|-\n| 1 || [[Mahakali, Darchula|Mahakali]] || Urban||21231 || 135.11 || 9||{{website|mahakalimundarchula.gov.np}}\n|-\n| 2 || [[Shailyasikhar]] || Urban||22060 ||117.81  || 9 || {{website|shailyashikharmun.gov.np}}\n|-\n| 3 || [[Malikarjun]] ||Rural || 15581 || 100.82 || 8||{{website|malikarjunmun.gov.np}}\n|-\n| 4 || Apihimal || Rural || 6779 || 613.95 || 6 || {{website|apihimalmun.gov.np}}\n|-\n| 5 || Duhun || Rural || 10818 || 65.35 || 5|| {{website|duhunmun.gov.np}}\n|-\n| 6 || [[Naugadh, Darchula|Naugadh]] || Rural || 15874 || 180.27 || 6 || {{website|naugadmun.gov.np}}\n|-\n| 7 || Marma || Rural || 14956 || 208.06 || 6 || {{website|marmamun.gov.np}}\n|-\n| 8 || Lekam || Rural || 14838 || 83.98 || 6 || {{website|lekammun.gov.np}}\n|-\n| 9 || [[Vyans]] || Rural || 10347 || 839.26 || 6 || {{website|vyansmun.gov.np}}\n|-\n|  || '''Darchula''' || '''District''' ||''' 132484''' || '''2344.61''' || '''61 '''|| {{website|ddcdarchula.gov.np}}\n|}\n\n===Former administrative divisions===\n{{Further|Former administrative units of Nepal}}\n{{See also|List of village development committees of Nepal#Darchula_District}}\nFormerly, Darchula had one municipality and many VDCs. VDCs were the local administrative units for villages.\n\nFulfilling the requirement of the new constitution of Nepal 2015, on 10 March 2017 all VDCs were nullified and formed new units after grouping VDCs.\n==Constituencies==\n{{Further|Pratinidhi Sabha}}\n{{Further|Pradesh Sabha}}\nDarchula District consists 1 [[House of Representatives (Nepal)|Parliamentary constituency]] and 2 [[Provincial Assembly of Province No. 1|Provincial constituencies]]:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Constituencies !! Type !! Area!! [[Member of Parliament|MP]]/[[Member of Legislative Assembly|MLA]]!!Party\n|-\n| Darchula 1 ||Parliamentary || whole Darchula district || Ganesh Singh Thagunna||[[Nepal Communist Party|NCP]]\n|-\n| Darchula 1(A) || Provincial || Lekam, Malikarjun, Mahakali, Duhun and byans) || Gelbu Singh Bohara ||[[Nepal Communist Party|NCP]]\n|-\n| Darchula 1(B) || Provincial || Shailyashikhar, Naugad, Marma, Apihimal || Man Bahadur Dhami||[[Nepal Communist Party|NCP]]\n|}\n\n==Demographics==\nThe number of male 63,609 and female 69,855. Decadal change(%) 9.40, annual growth rate 0.90%, sex ratio (males per 100 females) 91, absent (abroad) population 6,867, where number of male 5,880 and female 987. Total number of house 22,948. Total number of household 25,802. Average household size 5.17. Population density {{cvt|57|km2}}. The town has an Indian counterpart to its northwest, named [[Dharchula]]. The split between the two towns is just virtual as the traditions, culture, and lifestyle of the people living across both the regions are quite similar.{{citation needed|date=September 2018}}\n\n{{Pie chart\n|thumb=right\n|caption=Castes in Darchula District\n|label1=[[Chhetri]]\n|color1=Orange\n|value1=63.55\n\n|label2=[[Hill Brahmin]]\n|color2=DodgerBlue\n|value2=17.15\n\n|label3=[[Thakuri]]\n|color3=Yellow\n|value3=4.01\n\n|label4=Others\n|color4=Black\n|value4=15.39\n}}\n\n{{Pie chart\n |thumb = right\n |caption= Religion in Darchula district as of 2011.\n |label1 = [[Hinduism]]\n |value1 = 98.88 | color1 = Orange\n |label2 = [[Buddhism]]\n |value2 = 0.87 | color2 = Yellow\n |label3 = [[Prak\u1e5bti]]\n |value3 = 0.15 | color3 = LimeGreen\n |label4 = Christianity\n |value4 = 0.05 | color4 = DodgerBlue\n |label5 = [[Islam]]\n |value5 = 0.02 | color5 = Green\n |label6 = Other or not religious\n |value6 = 0.01 | color6 = Black\n }}\n\nMore than 56,000 people live in 8,989 households. About 58.4 percent of the population falls below the poverty line. Population composition is made up of different castes, such as Kshatriya 63.55%, Brahmin 17.15%, Thakuri 4.01%, Dalit and others contribute 15.39 percent. Hindu followers are high in numbers. Hindu, Buddhists, as well as others, regard nature as a gift from God and they worship nature their own way.<ref name=\"National Population and Housing Census 2011(National Report)\" />\n\n===Ethnic composition===\nThe majority ethnic group is Pahari [[Aryan|Arya]].  Castes of Darchula District are Brahmin, Chhetries, Dalit, Thakuri, Lohar, Kaine, Newar, Byansi, Bandhe, Sanyasi etc. Among them 85.19% HHs are Brahmin/Chheties/Thakuri, 10% Dalits, 0.12% Sauka and others are occupational caste groups. Sauka are indigenous inhabitant's caste group. The indigenous caste groups are dominated by migrants from other villages.\nThe Dalits (7.35%) and Thakuri (7.43%) share equal proportions and occupy the second largest group in the total population. Indigenous groups Byansi represent 1.32%, Lohar 1.38% and other minorities\u2019 correspondent to 1.48 percent.  Dalits are also defined as the Special Target Groups (STGs).<ref name=\"National Population and Housing Census 2011(National Report)\" />\n\n===Language===\nAt the time of the [[2011 Nepal census]], Darchula District had a population of 133,274. Of these, 95.9% spoke [[Doteli]], 2.5% [[Nepali language|Nepali]] and 0.5% [[Lepcha language|Lepcha]] as their first language.<ref>[https://cbs.gov.np/wp-content/upLoads/2018/12/Volume05Part02.pdf 2011 Nepal Census, Social Characteristics Tables]</ref>\n\n==Economic development==\nDarchula is one of the least developed districts of the country. The major socioeconomic indicator of Darchula District is still very poor. Life expectancy of these people was about 52 in 1996. About 89.90% of the total population depends upon agriculture. Substance agriculture, lack of basic infrastructure, difficult geophysical condition, traditional agricultural practice, low literacy rate and population growth are the root causes for deeply rooted poverty.<ref name=\"National Population and Housing Census 2011(National Report)\" />\n\n==Trade and business==\nTrade is one of the most important means of livelihood. Every year, people from the hills come with NTFP, ghee, and herbs to sell. Agriculture related commodities are sold in local bazaars (markets). People of Byans, Rapla go to Tibet to fill their needs for clothes and other commodities. Local carpets and wool products, handmade clothes, and NTFP bring in huge amounts of money to the VDCs. However, each and every respondent indicated that their income is invested in domestic use.\n\n==Tourism==\n[[Api Nampa Conservation Area]] is a famous gateway to Kailash Mansarobar's holy region located in Tibet. Many pilgrims pass through this Conservation Area to get to Kailash Pravat. Not only Nepalese but also foreigners visit Api Nampa Conservation Area to acquire satisfaction, spirituality and the boons of nature.\nThe first European, A. H. Savage Landor entered Nampa valley in 1899 and explored the glacier system. He travelled across the Tinkar valley and entered Tibet via the Lipu pass. In 1905, Dr. Longstaff visited this region. Then Swiss geologists A. Heim and A. Gansser visited the [[Api (mountain)|Api Himal]] area in 1936.\nThe elevation of Api Himal at the top is calculated to be 23,399&nbsp;ft. John Tyson and W. H. Murray explored this region in 1953. An Api group has been created to lure tourists wanting to see the geological features blending with nature and other natural assets. Sauka culture is also an attraction for tourist.\nApi Himal can be visited by going via Darchula Bazar, Huti, Sunsera, Rapla to base camp. It takes five days to reach there or travelers may go via Bitule, Makari Gad, Ghusa Village, Domilla, to Lolu at the base camp. Panoramic views of Himalayas are created by several peaks like Nampa, [[Jethi Bahurani]] and others.{{citation needed|date=September 2018}}\n\n==Media/radio partners==\nTo Promote local culture there are few FM radio stations: Radio Samad FM 102.6 MHz,<ref>{{cite web|title= 50.Radio Samad FM 102.6&nbsp;MHz|url=http://www.acorab.org.np/index.php?pagename=memberDetail&memberId=83}}</ref> Radio Naya Nepal FM 104.5&nbsp;MHz,<ref>{{cite web|title=Radio Naya Nepal FM 104.5&nbsp;MHz|url=http://www.nayanepalfm.com.np/}}</ref> Darchula FM, which are Community radio Stations.\n\n==Education==\n===Colleges and schools===\n*Darchula Multiple Campus\n*Gokuleshwar Higher Secondary School\n*Himalaya Higher Secondary School\n*Gokuleswar Multiple Campus \n*Sri Krishna Snatak Campus\n*Rastriya Campus\n*[[Mahendra Higher Secondary School]]\n*Shankarpur Higher Secondary School\n*Latinath Higher Secondary School\n*Srikrishana Higher Secondary School\n*Rastiya Higher Secondary School\n*Latinatha Higher Secondary School\n*Hunainath Secondary School Baaj (Mahara Village)\n*Hunainath Higher Secondary School\n*Janabikasa Higher Secondary School\n*Ganesh Binayak Higher Secondary School\n*Malikarjun Higher Secondary School\n*Krishana Higher Secondary School\n*Sarswati Higher Secondary School\n*Gurilamandu Higher Secondary School\n*Galainath Higher Secondary School\n*Satya Parkash Higher Secondary School\n*Sri Krishana Higher Secondary School\n*[[Apinampa Campus]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.un.org.np/sites/default/files/maps/district_maps/Darchula.pdf UN map of VDC boundaries, water features and roads in Darchula]\n*[https://www.facebook.com/DarchulaDistrict/ Darchula District On Facebook ]\n\n==See also==\n*{{statoids|id=ynp|title=Districts of Nepal}}\n{{Geographic location\n|Centre = Darchula\n|North = {{flagicon|China}} [[Burang County]] ([[Tibet Autonomous Region|Tibet]])\n|Northeast =\n|East = [[Bajhang District]]\n|Southeast = \n|South = [[Baitadi District]]\n|Southwest = \n|West = {{flagicon|India}} [[Pithoragarh district]] ([[Uttrakhand]])\n|Northwest = \n}}\n{{Darchula District}}\n{{Districts of Nepal}}\n\n{{coord|29.848464|N|80.543391|E|type:adm3rd_source:itwiki|display=title}}\n\n{{commons category|Darchula District}}\n\n[[Category:Darchula District|*]]\n[[Category:Nepal districts established in 1962]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| type                    = [[Districts of Nepal|District]]\n| name                    = Darchula District of nepal\n| native_name             = \u0926\u093e\u0930\u094d\u091a\u0941\u0932\u093e \u091c\u093f\u0932\u094d\u0932\u093e\n| nickname                = \n| native_name_lang        = <!-- ISO 639-2 code e.g. \"fr\" for French. If more than one, use {{lang}} instead -->\n| motto                   = \n| image_skyline           = Sunrise Lekam1.jpg\n| image_alt               = \n| image_caption           = Sunrise from Lekam rural municipality in Darchula, Nepal.\n| image_map               = Darchula Sudurpashchim locator.png\n| mapsize                 = 300\n| map_alt                 = \n| map_caption             = Location of Darchula District\n| image_map1              = \n| mapsize1                = 300\n| map_alt1                = \n| map_caption1            = \n| coordinates             = \n| coordinates_footnotes   = \n| subdivision_type        = Country\n| subdivision_name        = {{NPL}}\n| subdivision_type1       = [[Provinces of Nepal|Province]]\n| subdivision_name1       = [[Sudurpashchim Pradesh]]\n\n| parts_type              = [[Local self-government in Nepal|Municipality]]\n| parts_style             = coll\n| p1                      = [[List of cities in Nepal|'''Urban''']]\n| p2            