{"title_page": "Out of It (film)", "text_new": "{{short description|1969 film}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Out of It\n| image\t         = Out of It FilmPoster.jpeg\n| caption        = Film poster\n| director       = [[Paul Williams (director)|Paul Williams]]\n| producer       = [[Edward R. Pressman]]\n| writer         = Paul Williams\n| starring       = [[Barry Gordon]]<br>[[Jon Voight]]<br>[[Lada Edmund Jr.]]\n| music          = [[Michael Small]]\n| cinematography = [[John G. Avildsen]]\n| editing        = Ed Orshan\n| studio         = Pressman-Williams Enterprises, Inc.\n| distributor    = [[United Artists]]\n| released       = {{film date|1969|12}}\n| runtime        = 95 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $350,000<ref>Fellini Meets Bergman\nBy A. H. WEILER. New York Times (1923-Current file) [New York, N.Y] October 27, 1968: D15.</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Out of It''''' is a 1969 American [[comedy-drama]] film directed by [[Paul Williams (director)|Paul Williams]], and starring [[Barry Gordon]], [[Jon Voight]], [[Lada Edmund Jr.]], [[Gretchen Corbett]], and Peter Grad. It was entered into the [[20th Berlin International Film Festival]].<ref name=\"imdb\">{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0063401/awards |title=IMDB.com: Awards for Out of It |accessdate=March 10, 2010 |work=imdb.com}}</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Barry Gordon]] as Paul\n* [[Jon Voight]] as Russ\n* [[Lada Edmund Jr.]] as Christine\n* [[Gretchen Corbett]] as Barbara\n* [[Peter Grad]] as Steve\n* [[Martin Gray (actor)|Martin Gray]] as Draft Board\n* [[Oliver Berry]]\n* [[Leonard Gelber]] as Draft Board\n* [[Richard Coyle (actor)|Richard Coyle]]<!--don't change to [[Richard Coyle]] - he was born 5 years after film was made-->\n\n==Production==\nThe film was made before Voight's breakout performance in ''[[Midnight Cowboy]]'' but released after.<ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|page=5|title=Honest Ad Angle|date=July 16, 1969}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{AFI film|20629}}\n*{{IMDb title|id=0063401|title=Out of It}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Out Of It}}\n[[Category:1969 films]]\n[[Category:1960s comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:American comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:American coming-of-age films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Paul Williams]]\n[[Category:Films set in Long Island]]\n[[Category:United Artists films]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Michael Small]]\n[[Category:1969 directorial debut films]]\n\n\n{{1960s-comedy-film-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1969 film}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Out of It\n| image\t         = Out of It FilmPoster.jpeg\n| caption        = Film poster\n| director       = [[Paul Williams (director)|Paul Williams]]\n| producer       = [[Edward R. Pressman]]\n| writer         = Paul Williams\n| starring       = [[Barry Gordon]]<br>[[Jon Voight]]<br>[[Lada Edmund Jr.]]\n| music          = [[Michael Small]]\n| cinematography = [[John G. Avildsen]]\n| editing        = Ed Orshan\n| studio         = Pressman-Williams Enterprises, Inc.\n| distributor    = [[United Artists]]\n| released       = {{film date|1969|12}}\n| runtime        = 95 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $350,000<ref>Fellini Meets Bergman\nBy A. H. WEILER. New York Times (1923-Current file) [New York, N.Y] October 27, 1968: D15.</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Out of It''''' is a 1969 American [[comedy-drama]] film directed by [[Paul Williams (director)|Paul Williams]], and starring [[Barry Gordon]], [[Jon Voight]], [[Lada Edmund Jr.]], [[Gretchen Corbett]], and Peter Grad. It was entered into the [[20th Berlin International Film Festival]].<ref name=\"imdb\">{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0063401/awards |title=IMDB.com: Awards for Out of It |accessdate=March 10, 2010 |work=imdb.com}}</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Barry Gordon]] as Paul\n* [[Jon Voight]] as Russ\n* [[Lada Edmund Jr.]] as Christine\n* [[Gretchen Corbett]] as Barbara\n* [[Peter Grad]] as Steve\n* [[Martin Gray (actor)|Martin Gray]] as Draft Board\n* [[Oliver Berry]]\n* [[Leonard Gelber]] as Draft Board\n* [[Richard Coyle (actor)|Richard Coyle]]<!--don't change to [[Richard Coyle]] - he was born 5 years after film was made-->\n\n==Production==\nThe film was made before Voight's breakout performance in ''[[Midnight Cowboy]]'' but released after.<ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|page=5|title=Honest Ad Angle|date=July 16, 1969}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{AFI film|20629}}\n*{{IMDb title|id=0063401|title=Out of It}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Out Of It}}\n[[Category:1969 films]]\n[[Category:1960s comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:American comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:American coming-of-age films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Paul Williams]]\n[[Category:Films set in Long Island]]\n[[Category:United Artists films]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Michael Small]]\n[[Category:1969 directorial debut films]]\n\n\n{{1960s-comedy-film-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Lugnuts", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Out_of_It_(film)"}
{"title_page": "Valea lui Mihai", "text_new": "{{for|the village in Alba County|Vin\u021bu de Jos}}\n{{Infobox Romanian subdivision\n|type                   = town\n|county                 = Bihor\n|population_total       = auto\n|image_map = Valea lui Mihai jud Bihor.png\n|map_caption = Location in Bihor County\n|official_name=Valea lui Mihai\n|other_name=\u00c9rmih\u00e1lyfalva\n|image_skyline=RO BH Valea lui Mihai.jpg\n|image_shield=Coa_Romania_Town_\u00c9rmih\u00e1lyfalva.svg\n|leader_name= J\u00f3zsef Nyak\u00f3<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.2016bec.ro/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/SIAL2016_P_Lista_Moc-2.xlsx |title=Results of the 2016 local elections |publisher=Central Electoral Bureau |accessdate=2020-04-03 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n|leader_party=UDMR\n|area_total_km2=73.54\n|coordinates   = {{coord|47|31|12|N|22|7|48|E|region:RO|display=inline,title}}\n|website={{url|http://www.valealuimihai.ro/}}\n}}\n\n'''Valea lui Mihai''' ({{IPA-ro|\u02c8vale\u032fa luj mi\u02c8haj}}; {{lang-hu|\u00c9rmih\u00e1lyfalva}}) is a town in [[Romania]].\n==Geography==\nIt is located around 66&nbsp;km north-east of [[Oradea]], 9&nbsp;km from the [[Hungary|Hungarian]] border in [[Bihor County]], western [[Transylvania]], [[Romania]].\n\n==History==\nIn 1312, under [[Charles I of Hungary|Charles I]], it was allowed new trade privileges and then in 1459 was also allowed tax benefits privileges for its citizens. Later it was part of the [[Ottoman Empire]], which resulted in its depopulation, but the inhabitants subsequently returned. Thereafter, it was part of the [[Habsburg Monarchy]] up until the [[Austro-Hungarian Compromise of 1867]]. Then it became part of the [[Kingdom of Hungary]] within [[Austria-Hungary]]. \n\nAfter the breaking-up of Austria-Hungary in 1918/1920, the town became part of [[Romania]]. As a result of the [[Second Vienna Award]] it became a part of [[Hungary]] between 1940 and 1945. Since then it has been part of Romania. It was declared a town on three separate occasions: in 1844, 1930 and 1989.\n\n==Population==\n{{Historical populations\n|source = Census data\n|1992 |10505\n|2002 |10665\n|2011 |9688\n}}\n\nAccording to the last [[Demographics of Romania|census from 2011]] there were 9,668  people living within the city. \n\nOf this population, 81.03% are ethnic [[Hungarian people|Hungarians]], while 13.23% are ethnic [[Romanians]] and 1.3% others.<ref>[http://www.edrc.ro/recensamant.jsp?regiune_id=2140&judet_id=2141&localitate_id=2149 Romanian 2002 Census]</ref>\n\n==Image gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Catholic Church of Valea lui Mihai (Ermihalyfalva).jpg|The Roman Catholic church of the town\nFile:\u00c9rmih\u00e1lyfalva (Valea lui Mihai) - street.JPG|Street in Valea lui Mihai\nFile:Er-Mihalyfalva File6013.jpg|''Er-Mihalyfalva'' on Hungary stamp issued in 1871\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Valea lui Mihai}}\n* [http://www.shtetlinks.jewishgen.org/Valea_lui_Mihai/ Valea lui Mihai - ShtetLink]\n\n{{LocalitiesBihor}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Valea Lui Mihai}}\n[[Category:Populated places in Bihor County]]\n[[Category:Towns in Romania]]\n[[Category:Hungary\u2013Romania border crossings]]\n\n{{bihor-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{for|the village in Alba County|Vin\u021bu de Jos}}\n{{Infobox Romanian subdivision\n|type                   = town\n|county                 = Bihor\n|population_total       = auto\n|image_map = Valea lui Mihai jud Bihor.png\n|map_caption = Location in Bihor County\n|official_name=Valea lui Mihai\n|other_name=\u00c9rmih\u00e1lyfalva\n|image_skyline=RO BH Valea lui Mihai.jpg\n|image_shield=Coa_Romania_Town_\u00c9rmih\u00e1lyfalva.svg\n|leader_name=Nyak\u00f3 J\u00f3zsef\n|leader_party=UDMR\n|area_total_km2=73.54\n|coordinates   = {{coord|47|31|12|N|22|7|48|E|region:RO|display=inline,title}}\n|website={{url|http://www.valealuimihai.ro/}}\n}}\n\n'''Valea lui Mihai''' ({{IPA-ro|\u02c8vale\u032fa luj mi\u02c8haj}}; {{lang-hu|\u00c9rmih\u00e1lyfalva}}) is a town in [[Romania]].\n==Geography==\nIt is located around 66&nbsp;km north-east of [[Oradea]], 9&nbsp;km from the [[Hungary|Hungarian]] border in [[Bihor County]], western [[Transylvania]], [[Romania]].\n\n==History==\nIn 1312, under [[Charles I of Hungary|Charles I]], it was allowed new trade privileges and then in 1459 was also allowed tax benefits privileges for its citizens. Later it was part of the [[Ottoman Empire]], which resulted in its depopulation, but the inhabitants subsequently returned. Thereafter, it was part of the [[Habsburg Monarchy]] up until the [[Austro-Hungarian Compromise of 1867]]. Then it became part of the [[Kingdom of Hungary]] within [[Austria-Hungary]]. \n\nAfter the breaking-up of Austria-Hungary in 1918/1920, the town became part of [[Romania]]. As a result of the [[Second Vienna Award]] it became a part of [[Hungary]] between 1940 and 1945. Since then it has been part of Romania. It was declared a town on three separate occasions: in 1844, 1930 and 1989.\n\n==Population==\n{{Historical populations\n|source = Census data\n|1992 |10505\n|2002 |10665\n|2011 |9688\n}}\n\nAccording to the last [[Demographics of Romania|census from 2011]] there were 9,668  people living within the city. \n\nOf this population, 81.03% are ethnic [[Hungarian people|Hungarians]], while 13.23% are ethnic [[Romanians]] and 1.3% others.<ref>[http://www.edrc.ro/recensamant.jsp?regiune_id=2140&judet_id=2141&localitate_id=2149 Romanian 2002 Census]</ref>\n\n==Image gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Catholic Church of Valea lui Mihai (Ermihalyfalva).jpg|The Roman Catholic church of the town\nFile:\u00c9rmih\u00e1lyfalva (Valea lui Mihai) - street.JPG|Street in Valea lui Mihai\nFile:Er-Mihalyfalva File6013.jpg|''Er-Mihalyfalva'' on Hungary stamp issued in 1871\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Valea lui Mihai}}\n* [http://www.shtetlinks.jewishgen.org/Valea_lui_Mihai/ Valea lui Mihai - ShtetLink]\n\n{{LocalitiesBihor}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Valea Lui Mihai}}\n[[Category:Populated places in Bihor County]]\n[[Category:Towns in Romania]]\n[[Category:Hungary\u2013Romania border crossings]]\n\n{{bihor-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Markussep", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Valea_lui_Mihai"}
{"title_page": "Mewati gharana", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=January 2018}}\n{{More citations needed|date=August 2015}}\nThe '''Mewati gharana''' (also known as the '''Jaipur-Mewati gharana''')<ref>http://www.culturopedia.net/Music/gharanas.html</ref><ref>http://www.ipaac.org/Abhyankar.htm</ref><ref>http://www.ipaac.org/Sanjeev2015.htm</ref> is a [[Gharana|musical apprenticeship tribe]] of [[Hindustani classical music]]. Known for being [[Jasraj|Pandit Jasraj's]] musical lineage, the gharana was founded by brothers [[Mewati gharana#Utd. Ghagge Nazir Khan|Utd. Ghagge Nazir Khan]] and [[Mewati gharana#Utd. Wahid Khan (beenkar)|Utd. Wahid Khan (beenkar)]] of [[Rewa (princely state)|Bhopal]]<ref>http://mewatheritage.khamayati.org/about/</ref> in the late 19th century at the [[Jodhpur State|Jodhpur court]].<ref>https://www.academia.edu/34585877/Obituary_Rais_Khan</ref> Consequently, it is also known (though less commonly) as the '''Jodhpur Gharana'''.<ref>https://forum.chandrakantha.com/post/mewati-gharana-8674324?trail=45</ref><ref>https://www.facebook.com/LegendsofMewatiGharana/photos/a.109660156032330/109660159365663/?type=1&theater</ref>\n\nWith its own distinct aesthetics, stylings, practices, and repertoire, the gharana emerged as an offshoot of the [[Gwalior gharana|Gwalior]] and [[Qawwal Bacchon ka Gharana|Qawwal Bacchon (Delhi)]] musical traditions.<ref>http://thecompass.in/evolution-of-hindustani-music-patron-and-patronage-1181</ref> The gharana gained visibility in the late-20th century after [[Jasraj|Pt. Jasraj]] popularized the [[gayaki]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Nagarkar |first1=Samarth |title=Raga Sangeet: Understanding Hindustani Classical Vocal Music |date=2013 |publisher=Chhandayan, Inc. |location=New York}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nGhagge Nazir Khan and Wahid Khan are regarded as fountainheads of the Mewati gharana.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Afshan Ahmed |first1=Afshan |title=Pandit Jasraj brings his Mewati style of Hindustani classical music to Dubai |url=https://www.thenational.ae/arts-culture/music/pandit-jasraj-brings-his-mewati-style-of-hindustani-classical-music-to-dubai-1.297663 |accessdate=25 January 2019 |publisher=The National |date=December 15, 2013}}</ref> They were descendants of the [[Qawwal Bacchon gharana]] (Qawwal Bacchon Ka Gharana).<ref>{{cite book |last1=Roy |first1=Ashok |title=Music makers: living legends of Indian classical music |date=February 2, 2004 |publisher=Rupa & Co |page=97}}</ref>\n\n===Name===\nBrothers Ghagge Nazir Khan and Wahid Khan founded the Mewati Gharana, named after the region in [[Delhi]] from where their family hailed, [[Mewat]] (not the [[Mewar]] region of Rajasthan).<ref>{{cite book |last1=Chib |first1=Satyendra Krishen Sen |title=Companion to North Indian classical music |date=2004 |publisher=Munshiram Manoharlal Pub |page=171}}</ref>\n\n===Ancestry===\nGhagge Nazir Khan and Wahid Khan inherited the traditions of [[Qawwal Bacchon Ka Gharana|Qawwal Bacchon gayaki]] from their parents.<ref>https://www.thehindu.com/entertainment/music/pt-jasraj-a-star-of-mewati/article22761937.ece</ref> Their father, Bade Mohammed Khan, son of Shakkar Khan of Lucknow, emerged from the Qawwal Bacchon tradition.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Wade |first1=Bonnie C. |title=Khyal: Creativity Within North India's Classical Music Tradition |date=1984 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |location=Great Britain |page=37}}</ref> Their mother, a daughter of Haddu Khan of Gwalior, emerged from the Gwalior tradition. Through their union, Bade Mohammed Khan acquired the status of being a Gwalior gharana exponent and was regarded for his \"taan bazi\" repertoire.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Dhar |first1=Sunita |title=Senia gharana, its contribution to Indian classical music |date=1989 |publisher=Reliance Pub. House |page=15}}</ref><ref>https://swarajyamag.com/culture/all-roads-begin-from-the-gwalior-gharana</ref> Another offspring of Bade Mohammed Khan, Bade Mubarak Ali Khan, is said to have influenced [[Alladiya Khan|Alladiya Khan's]] [[Jaipur-Atrauli gharana|gayaki]] due to his proclivity for [[taan]]s.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Ha\u1e37ada\u1e47akara |first1=Babanar\u0101va |title=Aesthetics of Agra and Jaipur Traditions |date=2001 |publisher=Popular Prakashan |pages=16}}</ref>\n\nDue to politics and competition with Natthe Khan's family,<ref>http://www.sharadsathe.com/gwalior_gharana.html</ref> Bade Mohammed Khan relocated to [[Rewa district|Rewa]] in [[Bhopal]] as the court musician of the maharaja.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Mukhop\u0101dhy\u0101\u1e8fa |first1=Kum\u0101rapras\u0101da |title=The Lost World of Hindustani Music |date=2006 |publisher=Penguin Books |location=India |page=64}}</ref> Consequently, Ghagge Nazir Khan and Wahid Khan are associated with the Bhopal region in musical literature. Like their sibling, Bade Mubarak Ali Khan, Ghagge Nazir Khan and Wahid Khan moved to the [[Jaipur]] region following their father's demise, where the former was a court musician. Later, Ghagge Nazir Khan became court musician of Jodhpur.<ref>https://newslinemagazine.com/magazine/the-maestro-departs/</ref>\n\n====Geography====\nSeeking musical patronage, their ancestors immigrated from their origins in Delhi and Gwalior, settling first in Bhopal and later [[Jaipur State|western Rajasthan]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=D\u0101\u015ba\u015barm\u0101 |first1=Amala |title=Musicians of India: Past and Present : Gharanas of Hindustani Music and Genealogies |date=December 1, 1993 |publisher=Naya Prokash |pages=78, 239\u2013240}}</ref>\n\nThese migrations influenced new developments in the gharana's musical styles and aesthetics. Eventually, these changes resulted in the Mewati [[gayaki]] becoming distinct although reminiscent of the Gwalior and Qawwal Bacchon styles. Hence the gharana is considered both musically and genealogically different from these groups.\n\n====Genealogy====\nThe below illustration is based on the historical account provided by [[Siraj Khan]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Nadkarni |first1=Mohan |title=The Great Masters: profiles in Hindustani classical vocal music |date=1999 |publisher=HarperCollins Publishers India |location=India |page=38}}</ref>\n{{familytree/start|style=font-size:85%;line-height:100%;}}\n{{familytree| | | | | | |DHRUP|DHRUP=''Dhrupad Tradition''}}\n{{familytree| | | | | |,|-|^|-|.| | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | |}}\n{{familytree| | | | |WAZIR| |IMAMK|WAZIR=Wazir Khan <br>([[dhrupad|dhrupadiya]])\n            |IMAMK=Imdad Khan <br>([[dhrupad|dhrupadiya]])}}\n{{familytree| | | | | |,|-|-|-|+|-|-|-|.| | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | |}}\n{{familytree| | | | |WAHID| |GHAGG| |MUNAV|GHAGG=[[Mewati Gharana|'''Ghagge Nazir Khan''']] <br>(son)\n            |WAHID=[[Mewati Gharana|'''Wahid Khan''']] <br>(son)\n            |MUNAV=[[Mewati Gharana|Munavvar Khan]] <br>(son)}}\n\n{{familytree/end}}\n\n===Pedagogy===\nGhagge Nazir Khan passed on his musical tradition to his foremost disciples Munavvar Khan, Natthulal Pandit, and Chimanlal Pandit.<ref>http://www.visualfxindia.com/mewatigharana/html/tree.html</ref> Natthulal passed the tradition onto his nephew, Motiram, who shared this tradition with his brother, Jyotiram, around the start of the 20th century.<ref>http://www.visualfxindia.com/mewatigharana/html/ghulam_qadir.html</ref> During this period, Mewati musicians served under monarchical patronage as court musicians.{{cite AV media |people= |date= 2005|title= Gharana Aur Parampara|trans-title= Family and Tradition|medium= DVD|language= Hindi|url= |access-date= |archive-url= |archive-date= |format= |time= 60min|location= India|publisher= Doordarshan Archives|id= |isbn= |oclc= |quote= |ref= }}\n\nJyotiram later became a disciple of [[Rajab Ali Khan]], whose father, Manglu Khan,<ref>{{cite book |last1=Shafi |first1=Afshana |title=THE LEGACY OF GANGUBAI HANGAL |date=2017 |publisher=Horizon Books |page=125}}</ref> was a disciple of Bade Mohammed Khan and Bande Ali Khan (e.g. a member of the extended gharana).<ref>https://www.parrikar.org/vpl/profiles/rajabali_profile.pdf</ref> Motiram passed this tradition to his sons, Maniram and Pratap Narayan. After Motiram's unexpected demise, Maniram and Pratap Narayan were instrumental in grooming their younger brother, [[Jasraj]], in the Mewati tradition after the latter renounced playing [[tabla]], his primary training at the time. Jasraj was initially influenced by the music of [[Amir Khan (singer)|Amir Khan]] and [[Begum Akhtar]] but later developed a separate style. He introduced new stylistic elements into the traditional Mewati style, following the romanticism started by [[Omkarnath Thakur]] and producing a more emotive, devotional, rhythmic-conscious, and lyric-conscious style.\n\n===Pedagogical genealogy===\nA visual representation of Mewati gharana and its earlier roots.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://scontent-sea1-1.xx.fbcdn.net/v/t1.0-9/10689557_109712872693725_7531852658578182931_n.jpg?_nc_cat=107&_nc_ht=scontent-sea1-1.xx&oh=7385c37d33884b7f26c6f0ced6739c8c&oe=5C80BB2D | title=Mewati Gharana Lineage | accessdate=20 December 2018 }} {{unreliable?|date=December 2018}}</ref>\n\n{{familytree/start|style=font-size:85%;line-height:100%;}}\n{{familytree| | | | | | | | | | |GWALI| | |DELHI| | | | | | | | | |KIRAN| |DAGAR|GWALI=[[Gwalior gharana|''Gwalior Gharana<br>Guru Parampara'']]\n            |DELHI=[[Qawwal Bacchon gharana|''Qawwal Bacchon Gharana<br>Guru Parampara'']]\n            |KIRAN=[[Kirana gharana|''Kirana Gharana<br>Guru Parampara'']]\n            |DAGAR=[[Dagar gharana|''Dagar Gharana<br>Guru Parampara'']]}}\n{{familytree| | | | | | | | | | | |:| | | | |:| | | | | | | | | | | |:| | | |:| | |}}\n{{familytree| | | | | | | | | | |HADDU| | | |:| | | | | | | | | | |SADIQ| |BEHRA|HADDU=[[Haddu Khan|Haddu Khan<br>(Gwalior)]]\n            |SADIQ=[[Kirana gharana|Sadiq Ali Khan<br>(Kirana)]]\n            |BEHRA=[[Dagar gharana|Behram Khan<br>(Dagarbani)]]}}\n{{familytree| | | | | | | | | |F|~|A|7| | | |:| | | | | | | | | | | |:| | | |:| |}}\n{{familytree| | | | | | | | | |:| |DAUGH| |BADEM| | | | | | | | | | |L|~|V|~|J|DAUGH=[[Haddu Khan|(Daughter)]]\n            |BADEM=[[Bade Mohammed Khan|Bade Mohammed<br>Khan (Rewa)]]}}\n{{familytree| | | | | | | | |CHOTE| |L|~|V|~|J| | | | | | | | | | | | |BANDE|CHOTE=[[Chote Mohammed Khan|Chote Mohammed<br>Khan (son)]]\n            |BANDE=[[Bande Ali Khan|Bande Ali Khan<br>(beenkar)]]}}\n{{familytree| | | | | | | | | |:| | | | |:| | | | | | | | | | | | | | | |:|}}\n{{familytree| | | | | | | | | |:| | | |WARIS| | | | | | | | | | | | | | |:||WARIS=[[Waris Ali Khan|Waris Ali Khan<br>(son)]]\n            |MURAD=[[Murad Ali Khan|Murad Ali Khan<br>(son)]]\n            |MUNNA=[[Munnawar Ali Khan|Munnawar Ali Khan<br>(son)]]\n            |KUTUB=[[Kutub Ali Khan|Kutub Ali Khan<br>(son)]]\n            |MUBAR=Mubarak Ali Khan<br>(son, Jaipur Court)}}\n{{familytree| | | | | | | | | |L|~|~|V|~|J| | | | | | | | | | | | | |WAHID|WAHID=[[Mewati gharana#Utd. Wahid Khan|'''Wahid Khan'''<br>(co-founder,<br>beenkar)]]}}\n{{familytree| | | | | | | | | | | |GHAGG| | | | | | | | | | | | | | | |!|GHAGG=[[Mewati gharana#Utd. Ghagge Nazir Khan|'''Ghagge Nazir Khan'''<br>(co-founder,<br>vocalist)]]}}\n{{familytree| |,|-|-|-|-|-|-|-|-|-|-|+|-|-|-|.| |,|-|v|-|-|v|-|-|v|-|-|+|-|-|.|}}\n{{familytree|CHIMA| | | | | | | | |NATTH| |MUNAW|!|BEGUM| |!| |MAJID| |!| |LATIF|CHIMA=[[Pandit Chimanlal|Chimanlal<br>Pandit]]\n            |NATTH=[[Pandit Natthulal|Natthulal<br>Pandit]]\n            |MUNAW=[[Munavvar Ali Khan|Munavvar Ali<br>Khan]]\n            |MAJID=[[Majid Khan (beenkar)|Majid<br>Khan]]\n            |LATIF=[[Latif Khan (beenkar)|Latif<br>Khan]]\n            |BEGUM=[[Rais Khan|Begum<br>Hasibanbai]]}}\n{{familytree| | | | | | | | | | | | |!| | | |`|v|'| |!| |HAMID| |!| |SADDA| |!| |HAMID=[[Hamid Khan (beenkar)|Hamid<br>Khan]]\n            |SADDA=[[Saddan Khan|Saddan<br>Khan]]}}\n{{familytree| | | | | | | | |,|-|-|MOTIR| | |QADIR| |!| | | | |SHAFI| | | | |!| |MOTIR=[[Pandit Motiram|Motiram<br>Pandit]]\n            |QADIR=[[Ghulam Qadir Khan|Ghulam Qadir<br>Khan]]\n            |SHAFI=[[Mohammed Shafi|Mohammed<br>Shafi]]}}\n{{familytree| | | | | | | |JYOTI| | |!| | | | |!| | |!| | | | | | | | | | | |!|JYOTI=[[Pandit Jyotiram|Jyotiram<br>Pandit]]}}\n{{familytree| | | | | | | | |!| | | |!| | | |JAIWA|MOHAM| | | | | | | | | |KANIZ|JAIWA=[[Jaiwant Singhji Waghela|Jaiwant Singhji<br>Waghela]]\n            |KANIZ=[[Asad Khan (sitarist)|Begum Kaniz<br>Fatima]]\n            |MOHAM=[[Asad Khan (sitarist)|Mohammed<br>Khan]]}}\n{{familytree| | | | | | | | |)|-|-|-|+|-|-|-|v|'| | |!| | | | | | | | | | | |!|}}\n{{familytree| | | | | | | | |!| | | |!| | | |!| | | |!| | | | | | | | | | | |!|}}\n{{familytree| | | | | | | | |!| | |MANIR| |PRATA| | |!| | | | | | | | | | | |!|MANIR=[[Pandit Maniram|Maniram<br>Pandit]]\n            |PRATA=[[Pandit Pratap Narayan|Pratap Narayan<br>Pandit]]}}\n{{familytree| | | | | | | |PURAN| | |!| | | |!| | |RAISK| | | | | | | | | | |!|PURAN=[[Pandit Puranchandra|Puranchandra<br>Pandit]]\n            |RAISK=[[Rais Khan|Rais Khan<br>(sitarist)]]}}\n{{familytree| | | | | | | | | | | |JASRA| |JTNLT| | | | | | | | | | | | | |SIRAJ|JASRA=[[Pandit Jasraj|Jasraj<br>Pandit]]\n            |JTNLT=[[Jatin Lalit|Jatin Pandit &<br>Lalit Pandit]]\n            |SIRAJ=[[Asad Khan (sitarist)|Siraj Khan (sitarist)]]}}\n{{familytree| | | | | | | | | | | | |!| | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | |!|}}\n{{familytree| |,|-|v|-|v|-|v|-|v|-|v|^|v|-|v|-|v|-|v|-|v|-|v|-|v|-|.| | | | |!| | | | | |}}\n{{familytree|KRSNP|!|GIRSH|!|SHOBH|!| |!| |!| |!| |!| |!| |!| |!| |!| | | | |!|KRSNP=[[Krishnakant Parikh|Krishnakant<br>Parikh]]\n            |GIRSH=[[Girish Wazalwar|Girish<br>Wazalwar]]\n            |SHOBH=[[Shobha Abhyankar|Shobha<br>Abhyankar]]}}\n{{familytree| | | |!| | | |!| |`|-|+|-|(| |!| |!| |!| |!| |!| |!| |!| | | | |!|}}\n{{familytree| | |ARAWI| |RNMNS| |SANJV|!|MADHU|!|KALAR|!|TRIPT|!|SHWET| | |ASADK|RNMNS=[[Rattan Mohan Sharma|Rattan Mohan<br>Sharma]]\n            |ARAWI=[[Arwind Thatte]]<br>([[Pump organ|Harmoniumist]])\n            |SANJV=[[Sanjeev Abhyankar|Sanjeev<br>Abhyankar]]\n            |MADHU=[[Madhup Mudgal|Madhup<br>Mudgal]]\n            |SHWET=[[Shweta Jhaveri|Shweta<br>Jhaveri]]\n            |KALAR=[[Kala Ramnath]]<br>([[violin]]ist)\n            |TRIPT=[[Tripti Mukherjee|Tripti<br>Mukherjee]] \n            |ASADK=[[Asad Khan (sitarist)|Asad Khan<br>(sitarist)]]}}\n{{familytree| | | | | | | | | | | | |NAADR| |ANKIT| |PTBCJ| |RAMES|NAADR=[[Sandeep Ranade|Sandeep<br>Ranade]]\n            |MADHU=[[Madhup Mudgal|Madhup<br>Mudgal]]\n            |RAMES=[[Ramesh Narayan|Ramesh<br>Narayan]]\n            |ANKIT=[[Ankita Joshi|Ankita<br>Joshi]]\n            |PTBCJ=[[Pritam Bhattacharjee|Pritam<br>Bhattacharjee]]}}\n{{familytree/end}}\n\n==Overview==\n[[File:Sandeep Ranade with Milind Kulkarni and Nilesh Randive in Sangli.jpg|thumb|Mewati Gharana singer Sandeep Ranade performs at Bhave Natya Mandir, Sangli in December 2012.]]\n\n===Aesthetic Approaches===\nThough the [[gayaki]] has roots in the style and trends of the [[Gwalior gharana|Gwalior]] and [[Qawwali Bacchon Ka Gharana|Delhi]], the Mewati gayaki has some distinct qualities. The Mewati gayaki emphasizes the importance of [[bhava]] and literature ([[bandish]]).<ref>https://www.culturalindia.net/indian-music/hindustani-gharanas.html</ref> The gayaki includes substantial use of [[Sargam (music)|sargam]] and [[tihai]]s.<ref>http://harmonyom.blogspot.com/2010/11/ptmaniram-and-brothers-22.html</ref> In a crude sense, the approach to [[Taan (music)|taankari]] is similar to the [[Patiala Gharana|Patiala gayaki]] and [[Tappa|Tappa Gayaki]] in execution but is closer to the [[Gwalior Gharana|Gwalior gayaki]] in application.\n\nThe gayaki's [[meend]] applications have been regarded for their smoothness and naturalness.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Chatterjee |first1=Partha |title=At the crossroads |url=https://fountainink.in/reportage/at-the-crossroads |accessdate=25 January 2019 |publisher=foundtainink.in |date=December 6, 2017}}</ref>\n\n====Philosophy====\n[[Pandit Maniram|Maniram]] and [[Pandit Jasraj|Jasraj]] have described the essential philosophy of the Mewati tradition as based on \"shuddha vani\" (pure sound), \"shuddha mudra\" (pure expression), and \"shuddha sur\" (pure notes).<ref>{{cite book |last1=Goswami |first1=O |title=The Story Of Indian Music |date=1957 |publisher=Asia Publishing House |page=180 |url=https://archive.org/stream/TheStoryOfIndianMusicO.Goswami1957/The%20Story%20of%20Indian%20Music_O.Goswami_1957_djvu.txt}}</ref><ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=th21X-7T0G4</ref>\n\n====Religious themes====\nThrough [[Sufi|Sufiana mausiqi]] and [[Kirtankar|bhaktic]] influences, the Mewati gayaki includes theistic and spiritual elements, where religious verses from [[Hinduism]] and [[Shia Islam]] (especially [[Ismailism]]) are incorporated not only in the grammatical content of the music, but as intrinsic elements in melodic expression.<ref name=\"Mohan Nadkarni on Rajashthani Music\">{{cite news|last1=Nadkarni|first1=Mohan|title=Hindustani Music in Rajasthan|url=http://www.mohannadkarni.org/hindustani-music-in-rajasthan/|newspaper=The Illustrated Weekly of India|date=29 June 1980|accessdate=30 October 2018}}</ref> Jaiwant Singhji<ref>https://www.parrikar.org/hindustani/todi/</ref> and Jasraj contributed numerous devotional compositions to the gharana's repertoire.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Zutshi |first1=Minna |title=Sangeet Samrat |url=https://www.tribuneindia.com/2006/20060422/saturday/main1.htm |accessdate=25 January 2019 |publisher=The Tribune (India) |date=April 22, 2006}}</ref>\n\nSome contemporary compositions invoke the name and attributes of [[Aga Khan]] as the manifest [[Imam]] and the tenth incarnation of Lord [[Vishnu]] according to the [[dashavatara]].{{citation needed|date=November 2016}} The verse \"Om Shri Anant Hari Naaraaya\u00f1\" is typically invoked as the initiation of a performance, and as the grammatical medium for an [[alap]].{{citation needed|date=January 2019}}\n\n===Specialty ragas and compositions===\nThe Mewati Gharana holds raags unique to its tradition.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Singhji Waghela |first1=Jaiwant |title=Shri Sangeet Saurabh |date=1974 |location=Sanand, Gujarat}}</ref> These include:\n* Raag Jaiwanti Todi: A mixture of raags [[Ahir Bhairav]] and [[Todi (raga)|Todi]], created by Jaiwant Singhji.\n* Raag Jaiwant Sarang: A mixture of raags [[Jaijaiwanti]] and [[Sarang (raga)|Sarang]], created by Jaiwant Singhji.\n* Raag Gyaankali: Inspired by Raag [[Gorakh Kalyan]], created by Jaiwant Singhji.\n* Raag Rajrajeshwari: Created by Jaiwant Singhji.\n* Raag Bagkauns: Created by Jaiwant Singhji.\n* Raag Din Ki Puriya\n* Raag Audav Bageshree\n* Raag Khamaj Bahar\n* Raag Bhavani Bahar\n\n===Haveli Sangeet===\nInformed by the gharana's kirtankar tradition, Jasraj researched the [[haveli sangeet]] of Mathura and Brindavan. Consequently, many devotional compositions have been brought into the gharana's repertoire.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Ray |first1=N. R. |title=Dictionary of National Biography |date=1990 |publisher=Institute of Historical Studies |location=Calcutta |page=173}}</ref>\n\n==Members==\n===Utd. Ghagge Nazir Khan===\n{{Redirect|Ghagge Nazir Khan|other uses|Mewati Gharana}}\n'''\"Ghagge\" Nazir Khan''' (c. 1850 - c. 1920) was born to Imdad Khan, a dhrupadiya, in the [[Mewat|Mewat region]]. He learned vocal music from Utd. Chote Mohammed Khan (his maternal uncle) and Utd. Waris Ali Khan (his elder brother).<ref>http://www.visualfxindia.com/mewatigharana/html/ghagge_nazir.html</ref> He had no children. He taught music to Pt. Natthhulal, Pt. Chimmanlal, and Utd. Munavvar Khan (his younger brother).\n\n===Utd. Wahid Khan (beenkar)===\n{{Redirect|Wahid Khan (beenkar)|other uses|Mewati Gharana}}\n'''Wahid Khan''' (c. 1840 - 1933) was born to Imdad Khan, a dhrupadiya, in the [[Mewat|Mewat region]]. He learned [[Rudra Veena|rudra veena]] from [[Bande Ali Khan|Utd. Bande Ali Khan]] (his maternal uncle through marriage).<ref>http://www.visualfxindia.com/mewatigharana/html/wahidkhan.html</ref> Influenced by the Dhrupad ang, Wahid Khan taught instrumental music to his six children who also became musicians.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Music of Haryana]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Mewati gharana| ]]\n[[Category:Vocal gharanas]]\n[[Category:Mewat]]\n[[Category:Rajasthani culture]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=January 2018}}\n{{More citations needed|date=August 2015}}\nThe '''Mewati gharana''' (also known as the '''Jaipur-Mewati gharana''')<ref>http://www.culturopedia.net/Music/gharanas.html</ref><ref>http://www.ipaac.org/Abhyankar.htm</ref><ref>http://www.ipaac.org/Sanjeev2015.htm</ref> is a [[Gharana|musical apprenticeship tribe]] of [[Hindustani classical music]]. Known for being [[Jasraj|Pandit Jasraj's]] musical lineage, the gharana was founded by brothers [[Mewati gharana#Utd. Ghagge Nazir Khan|Utd. Ghagge Nazir Khan]] and [[Mewati gharana#Utd. Wahid Khan (beenkar)|Utd. Wahid Khan (beenkar)]] of [[Rewa (princely state)|Bhopal]]<ref>http://mewatheritage.khamayati.org/about/</ref> in the late 19th century at the [[Jodhpur State|Jodhpur court]].<ref>https://www.academia.edu/34585877/Obituary_Rais_Khan</ref> Consequently, it is also known (though less commonly) as the '''Jodhpur Gharana'''.<ref>https://forum.chandrakantha.com/post/mewati-gharana-8674324?trail=45</ref><ref>https://www.facebook.com/LegendsofMewatiGharana/photos/a.109660156032330/109660159365663/?type=1&theater</ref>\n\nWith its own distinct aesthetics, stylings, practices, and repertoire, the gharana emerged as an offshoot of the [[Gwalior gharana|Gwalior]] and [[Qawwal Bacchon ka Gharana|Qawwal Bacchon (Delhi)]] musical traditions.<ref>http://thecompass.in/evolution-of-hindustani-music-patron-and-patronage-1181</ref> The gharana gained visibility in the late-20th century after [[Jasraj|Pt. Jasraj]] popularized the [[gayaki]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Nagarkar |first1=Samarth |title=Raga Sangeet: Understanding Hindustani Classical Vocal Music |date=2013 |publisher=Chhandayan, Inc. |location=New York}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nGhagge Nazir Khan and Wahid Khan are regarded as fountainheads of the Mewati gharana.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Afshan Ahmed |first1=Afshan |title=Pandit Jasraj brings his Mewati style of Hindustani classical music to Dubai |url=https://www.thenational.ae/arts-culture/music/pandit-jasraj-brings-his-mewati-style-of-hindustani-classical-music-to-dubai-1.297663 |accessdate=25 January 2019 |publisher=The National |date=December 15, 2013}}</ref> They were descendants of the [[Qawwal Bacchon gharana]] (Qawwal Bacchon Ka Gharana).<ref>{{cite book |last1=Roy |first1=Ashok |title=Music makers: living legends of Indian classical music |date=February 2, 2004 |publisher=Rupa & Co |page=97}}</ref>\n\n===Name===\nBrothers Ghagge Nazir Khan and Wahid Khan founded the Mewati Gharana, named after the region in [[Delhi]] from where their family hailed, [[Mewat]] (not the [[Mewar]] region of Rajasthan).<ref>{{cite book |last1=Chib |first1=Satyendra Krishen Sen |title=Companion to North Indian classical music |date=2004 |publisher=Munshiram Manoharlal Pub |page=171}}</ref>\n\n===Ancestry===\nGhagge Nazir Khan and Wahid Khan inherited the traditions of [[Qawwal Bacchon Ka Gharana|Qawwal Bacchon gayaki]] from their parents.<ref>https://www.thehindu.com/entertainment/music/pt-jasraj-a-star-of-mewati/article22761937.ece</ref> Their father, Bade Mohammed Khan, son of Shakkar Khan of Lucknow, emerged from the Qawwal Bacchon tradition.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Wade |first1=Bonnie C. |title=Khyal: Creativity Within North India's Classical Music Tradition |date=1984 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |location=Great Britain |page=37}}</ref> Their mother, a daughter of Haddu Khan of Gwalior, emerged from the Gwalior tradition. Through their union, Bade Mohammed Khan acquired the status of being a Gwalior gharana exponent and was regarded for his \"taan bazi\" repertoire.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Dhar |first1=Sunita |title=Senia gharana, its contribution to Indian classical music |date=1989 |publisher=Reliance Pub. House |page=15}}</ref><ref>https://swarajyamag.com/culture/all-roads-begin-from-the-gwalior-gharana</ref> Another offspring of Bade Mohammed Khan, Bade Mubarak Ali Khan, is said to have influenced [[Alladiya Khan|Alladiya Khan's]] [[Jaipur-Atrauli gharana|gayaki]] due to his proclivity for [[taan]]s.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Ha\u1e37ada\u1e47akara |first1=Babanar\u0101va |title=Aesthetics of Agra and Jaipur Traditions |date=2001 |publisher=Popular Prakashan |pages=16}}</ref>\n\nDue to politics and competition with Natthe Khan's family,<ref>http://www.sharadsathe.com/gwalior_gharana.html</ref> Bade Mohammed Khan relocated to [[Rewa district|Rewa]] in [[Bhopal]] as the court musician of the maharaja.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Mukhop\u0101dhy\u0101\u1e8fa |first1=Kum\u0101rapras\u0101da |title=The Lost World of Hindustani Music |date=2006 |publisher=Penguin Books |location=India |page=64}}</ref> Consequently, Ghagge Nazir Khan and Wahid Khan are associated with the Bhopal region in musical literature. Like their sibling, Bade Mubarak Ali Khan, Ghagge Nazir Khan and Wahid Khan moved to the [[Jaipur]] region following their father's demise, where the former was a court musician. Later, Ghagge Nazir Khan became court musician of Jodhpur.<ref>https://newslinemagazine.com/magazine/the-maestro-departs/</ref>\n\n====Geography====\nSeeking musical patronage, their ancestors immigrated from their origins in Delhi and Gwalior, settling first in Bhopal and later [[Jaipur State|western Rajasthan]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=D\u0101\u015ba\u015barm\u0101 |first1=Amala |title=Musicians of India: Past and Present : Gharanas of Hindustani Music and Genealogies |date=December 1, 1993 |publisher=Naya Prokash |pages=78, 239\u2013240}}</ref>\n\nThese migrations influenced new developments in the gharana's musical styles and aesthetics. Eventually, these changes resulted in the Mewati [[gayaki]] becoming distinct although reminiscent of the Gwalior and Qawwal Bacchon styles. Hence the gharana is considered both musically and genealogically different from these groups.\n\n====Genealogy====\nThe below illustration is based on the historical account provided by [[Siraj Khan]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Nadkarni |first1=Mohan |title=The Great Masters: profiles in Hindustani classical vocal music |date=1999 |publisher=HarperCollins Publishers India |location=India |page=38}}</ref>\n{{familytree/start|style=font-size:85%;line-height:100%;}}\n{{familytree| | | | | | |DHRUP|DHRUP=''Dhrupad Tradition''}}\n{{familytree| | | | | |,|-|^|-|.| | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | |}}\n{{familytree| | | | |WAZIR| |IMAMK|WAZIR=Wazir Khan <br>([[dhrupad|dhrupadiya]])\n            |IMAMK=Imdad Khan <br>([[dhrupad|dhrupadiya]])}}\n{{familytree| | | | | |,|-|-|-|+|-|-|-|.| | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | |}}\n{{familytree| | | | |WAHID| |GHAGG| |MUNAV|GHAGG=[[Mewati Gharana|'''Ghagge Nazir Khan''']] <br>(son)\n            |WAHID=[[Mewati Gharana|'''Wahid Khan''']] <br>(son)\n            |MUNAV=[[Mewati Gharana|Munavvar Khan]] <br>(son)}}\n\n{{familytree/end}}\n\n===Pedagogy===\nGhagge Nazir Khan passed on his musical tradition to his foremost disciples Munavvar Khan, Natthulal Pandit, and Chimanlal Pandit.<ref>http://www.visualfxindia.com/mewatigharana/html/tree.html</ref> Natthulal passed the tradition onto his nephew, Motiram, who shared this tradition with his brother, Jyotiram, around the start of the 20th century.<ref>http://www.visualfxindia.com/mewatigharana/html/ghulam_qadir.html</ref> During this period, Mewati musicians served under monarchical patronage as court musicians.{{cite AV media |people= |date= 2005|title= Gharana Aur Parampara|trans-title= Family and Tradition|medium= DVD|language= Hindi|url= |access-date= |archive-url= |archive-date= |format= |time= 60min|location= India|publisher= Doordarshan Archives|id= |isbn= |oclc= |quote= |ref= }}\n\nJyotiram later became a disciple of [[Rajab Ali Khan]], whose father, Manglu Khan,<ref>{{cite book |last1=Shafi |first1=Afshana |title=THE LEGACY OF GANGUBAI HANGAL |date=2017 |publisher=Horizon Books |page=125}}</ref> was a disciple of Bade Mohammed Khan and Bande Ali Khan (e.g. a member of the extended gharana).<ref>https://www.parrikar.org/vpl/profiles/rajabali_profile.pdf</ref> Motiram passed this tradition to his sons, Maniram and Pratap Narayan. After Motiram's unexpected demise, Maniram and Pratap Narayan were instrumental in grooming their younger brother, [[Jasraj]], in the Mewati tradition after the latter renounced playing [[tabla]], his primary training at the time. Jasraj was initially influenced by the music of [[Amir Khan (singer)|Amir Khan]] and [[Begum Akhtar]] but later developed a separate style. He introduced new stylistic elements into the traditional Mewati style, following the romanticism started by [[Omkarnath Thakur]] and producing a more emotive, devotional, rhythmic-conscious, and lyric-conscious style.\n\n===Pedagogical genealogy===\nA visual representation of Mewati gharana and its earlier roots.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://scontent-sea1-1.xx.fbcdn.net/v/t1.0-9/10689557_109712872693725_7531852658578182931_n.jpg?_nc_cat=107&_nc_ht=scontent-sea1-1.xx&oh=7385c37d33884b7f26c6f0ced6739c8c&oe=5C80BB2D | title=Mewati Gharana Lineage | accessdate=20 December 2018 }} {{unreliable?|date=December 2018}}</ref>\n\n{{familytree/start|style=font-size:85%;line-height:100%;}}\n{{familytree| | | | | | | | | | |GWALI| | |DELHI| | | | | | | | | |KIRAN| |DAGAR|GWALI=[[Gwalior gharana|''Gwalior Gharana<br>Guru Parampara'']]\n            |DELHI=[[Qawwal Bacchon gharana|''Qawwal Bacchon Gharana<br>Guru Parampara'']]\n            |KIRAN=[[Kirana gharana|''Kirana Gharana<br>Guru Parampara'']]\n            |DAGAR=[[Dagar gharana|''Dagar Gharana<br>Guru Parampara'']]}}\n{{familytree| | | | | | | | | | | |:| | | | |:| | | | | | | | | | | |:| | | |:| | |}}\n{{familytree| | | | | | | | | | |HADDU| | | |:| | | | | | | | | | |SADIQ| |BEHRA|HADDU=[[Haddu Khan|Haddu Khan<br>(Gwalior)]]\n            |SADIQ=[[Kirana gharana|Sadiq Ali Khan<br>(Kirana)]]\n            |BEHRA=[[Dagar gharana|Behram Khan<br>(Dagarbani)]]}}\n{{familytree| | | | | | | | | |F|~|A|7| | | |:| | | | | | | | | | | |:| | | |:| |}}\n{{familytree| | | | | | | | | |:| |DAUGH| |BADEM| | | | | | | | | | |L|~|V|~|J|DAUGH=[[Haddu Khan|(Daughter)]]\n            |BADEM=[[Bade Mohammed Khan|Bade Mohammed<br>Khan (Rewa)]]}}\n{{familytree| | | | | | | | |CHOTE| |L|~|V|~|J| | | | | | | | | | | | |BANDE|CHOTE=[[Chote Mohammed Khan|Chote Mohammed<br>Khan (son)]]\n            |BANDE=[[Bande Ali Khan|Bande Ali Khan<br>(beenkar)]]}}\n{{familytree| | | | | | | | | |:| | | | |:| | | | | | | | | | | | | | | |:|}}\n{{familytree| | | | | | | | | |:| | | |WARIS| | | | | | | | | | | | | | |:||WARIS=[[Waris Ali Khan|Waris Ali Khan<br>(son)]]\n            |MURAD=[[Murad Ali Khan|Murad Ali Khan<br>(son)]]\n            |MUNNA=[[Munnawar Ali Khan|Munnawar Ali Khan<br>(son)]]\n            |KUTUB=[[Kutub Ali Khan|Kutub Ali Khan<br>(son)]]\n            |MUBAR=Mubarak Ali Khan<br>(son, Jaipur Court)}}\n{{familytree| | | | | | | | | |L|~|~|V|~|J| | | | | | | | | | | | | |WAHID|WAHID=[[Mewati gharana#Utd. Wahid Khan|'''Wahid Khan'''<br>(co-founder,<br>beenkar)]]}}\n{{familytree| | | | | | | | | | | |GHAGG| | | | | | | | | | | | | | | |!|GHAGG=[[Mewati gharana#Utd. Ghagge Nazir Khan|'''Ghagge Nazir Khan'''<br>(co-founder,<br>vocalist)]]}}\n{{familytree| |,|-|-|-|-|-|-|-|-|-|-|+|-|-|-|.| |,|-|v|-|-|v|-|-|v|-|-|+|-|-|.|}}\n{{familytree|CHIMA| | | | | | | | |NATTH| |MUNAW|!|BEGUM| |!| |MAJID| |!| |LATIF|CHIMA=[[Pandit Chimanlal|Chimanlal<br>Pandit]]\n            |NATTH=[[Pandit Natthulal|Natthulal<br>Pandit]]\n            |MUNAW=[[Munavvar Ali Khan|Munavvar Ali<br>Khan]]\n            |MAJID=[[Majid Khan (beenkar)|Majid<br>Khan]]\n            |LATIF=[[Latif Khan (beenkar)|Latif<br>Khan]]\n            |BEGUM=[[Rais Khan|Begum<br>Hasibanbai]]}}\n{{familytree| | | | | | | | | | | | |!| | | |`|v|'| |!| |HAMID| |!| |SADDA| |!| |HAMID=[[Hamid Khan (beenkar)|Hamid<br>Khan]]\n            |SADDA=[[Saddan Khan|Saddan<br>Khan]]}}\n{{familytree| | | | | | | | |,|-|-|MOTIR| | |QADIR| |!| | | | |SHAFI| | | | |!| |MOTIR=[[Pandit Motiram|Motiram<br>Pandit]]\n            |QADIR=[[Ghulam Qadir Khan|Ghulam Qadir<br>Khan]]\n            |SHAFI=[[Mohammed Shafi|Mohammed<br>Shafi]]}}\n{{familytree| | | | | | | |JYOTI| | |!| | | | |!| | |!| | | | | | | | | | | |!|JYOTI=[[Pandit Jyotiram|Jyotiram<br>Pandit]]}}\n{{familytree| | | | | | | | |!| | | |!| | | |JAIWA|MOHAM| | | | | | | | | |KANIZ|JAIWA=[[Jaiwant Singhji Waghela|Jaiwant Singhji<br>Waghela]]\n            |KANIZ=[[Asad Khan (sitarist)|Begum Kaniz<br>Fatima]]\n            |MOHAM=[[Asad Khan (sitarist)|Mohammed<br>Khan]]}}\n{{familytree| | | | | | | | |)|-|-|-|+|-|-|-|v|'| | |!| | | | | | | | | | | |!|}}\n{{familytree| | | | | | | | |!| | | |!| | | |!| | | |!| | | | | | | | | | | |!|}}\n{{familytree| | | | | | | | |!| | |MANIR| |PRATA| | |!| | | | | | | | | | | |!|MANIR=[[Pandit Maniram|Maniram<br>Pandit]]\n            |PRATA=[[Pandit Pratap Narayan|Pratap Narayan<br>Pandit]]}}\n{{familytree| | | | | | | |PURAN| | |!| | | |!| | |RAISK| | | | | | | | | | |!|PURAN=[[Pandit Puranchandra|Puranchandra<br>Pandit]]\n            |RAISK=[[Rais Khan|Rais Khan<br>(sitarist)]]}}\n{{familytree| | | | | | | | | | | |JASRA| |JTNLT| | | | | | | | | | | | | |SIRAJ|JASRA=[[Pandit Jasraj|Jasraj<br>Pandit]]\n            |JTNLT=[[Jatin Lalit|Jatin Pandit &<br>Lalit Pandit]]\n            |SIRAJ=[[Asad Khan (sitarist)|Siraj Khan (sitarist)]]}}\n{{familytree| | | | | | | | | | | | |!| | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | | |!|}}\n{{familytree| |,|-|v|-|v|-|v|-|v|-|v|^|v|-|v|-|v|-|v|-|v|-|v|-|v|-|.| | | | |!| | | | | |}}\n{{familytree|KRSNP|!|GIRSH|!|SHOBH|!| |!| |!| |!| |!| |!| |!| |!| |!| | | | |!|KRSNP=[[Krishnakant Parikh|Krishnakant<br>Parikh]]\n            |GIRSH=[[Girish Wazalwar|Girish<br>Wazalwar]]\n            |SHOBH=[[Shobha Abhyankar|Shobha<br>Abhyankar]]}}\n{{familytree| | | |!| | | |!| |`|-|+|-|(| |!| |!| |!| |!| |!| |!| |!| | | | |!|}}\n{{familytree| | |ARAWI| |RNMNS| |SANJV|!|MADHU|!|KALAR|!|TRIPT|!|SHWET| | |ASADK|RNMNS=[[Rattan Mohan Sharma|Rattan Mohan<br>Sharma]]\n            |ARAWI=[[Arwind Thatte]]<br>([[Pump organ|Harmoniumist]])\n            |SANJV=[[Sanjeev Abhyankar|Sanjeev<br>Abhyankar]]\n            |MADHU=[[Madhup Mudgal|Madhup<br>Mudgal]]\n            |SHWET=[[Shweta Jhaveri|Shweta<br>Jhaveri]]\n            |KALAR=[[Kala Ramnath]]<br>([[violin]]ist)\n            |TRIPT=[[Tripti Mukherjee|Tripti<br>Mukherjee]] \n            |ASADK=[[Asad Khan (sitarist)|Asad Khan<br>(sitarist)]]}}\n{{familytree| | | | | | | | | | | | |NAADR| |ANKIT| |PTBCJ| |RAMES|NAADR=[[Sandeep Ranade|Sandeep<br>Ranade]]\n            |MADHU=[[Madhup Mudgal|Madhup<br>Mudgal]]\n            |RAMES=[[Ramesh Narayan|Ramesh<br>Narayan]]\n            |ANKIT=[[Ankita Joshi|Ankita<br>Joshi]]\n            |PTBCJ=[[Pritam Bhattacharjee|Pritam<br>Bhattacharjee]]}}\n{{familytree/end}}\n\n==Overview==\n[[File:Sandeep Ranade with Milind Kulkarni and Nilesh Randive in Sangli.jpg|thumb|Mewati Gharana singer Sandeep Ranade performs at Bhave Natya Mandir, Sangli in December 2012.]]\n\n===Aesthetic Approaches===\nThough the [[gayaki]] has roots in the style and trends of the [[Gwalior gharana|Gwalior]] and [[Qawwali Bacchon Ka Gharana|Delhi]], the Mewati gayaki has some distinct qualities. The Mewati gayaki emphasizes the importance of [[bhava]] and literature ([[bandish]]).<ref>https://www.culturalindia.net/indian-music/hindustani-gharanas.html</ref> The gayaki includes substantial use of [[Sargam (music)|sargam]] and [[tihai]]s.<ref>http://harmonyom.blogspot.com/2010/11/ptmaniram-and-brothers-22.html</ref> In a crude sense, the approach to [[Taan (music)|taankari]] is similar to the [[Patiala Gharana|Patiala gayaki]] and [[Tappa|Tappa Gayaki]] in execution but is closer to the [[Gwalior Gharana|Gwalior gayaki]] in application.\n\nThe gayaki's [[meend]] applications have been regarded for their smoothness and naturalness.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Chatterjee |first1=Partha |title=At the crossroads |url=https://fountainink.in/reportage/at-the-crossroads |accessdate=25 January 2019 |publisher=foundtainink.in |date=December 6, 2017}}</ref>\n\n====Philosophy====\n[[Pandit Maniram|Maniram]] and [[Pandit Jasraj|Jasraj]] have described the essential philosophy of the Mewati tradition as based on \"shuddha vani\" (pure sound), \"shuddha mudra\" (pure expression), and \"shuddha sur\" (pure notes).<ref>{{cite book |last1=Goswami |first1=O |title=The Story Of Indian Music |date=1957 |publisher=Asia Publishing House |page=180 |url=https://archive.org/stream/TheStoryOfIndianMusicO.Goswami1957/The%20Story%20of%20Indian%20Music_O.Goswami_1957_djvu.txt}}</ref><ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=th21X-7T0G4</ref>\n\n====Religious themes====\nThrough [[Sufi|Sufiana mausiqi]] and [[Kirtankar|bhaktic]] influences, the Mewati gayaki includes theistic and spiritual elements, where religious verses from [[Hinduism]] and [[Shia Islam]] (especially [[Ismailism]]) are incorporated not only in the grammatical content of the music, but as intrinsic elements in melodic expression.<ref name=\"Mohan Nadkarni on Rajashthani Music\">{{cite news|last1=Nadkarni|first1=Mohan|title=Hindustani Music in Rajasthan|url=http://www.mohannadkarni.org/hindustani-music-in-rajasthan/|newspaper=The Illustrated Weekly of India|date=29 June 1980|accessdate=30 October 2018}}</ref> Jaiwant Singhji<ref>https://www.parrikar.org/hindustani/todi/</ref> and Jasraj contributed numerous devotional compositions to the gharana's repertoire.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Zutshi |first1=Minna |title=Sangeet Samrat |url=https://www.tribuneindia.com/2006/20060422/saturday/main1.htm |accessdate=25 January 2019 |publisher=The Tribune (India) |date=April 22, 2006}}</ref>\n\nSome contemporary compositions invoke the name and attributes of [[Aga Khan]] as the manifest [[Imam]] and the tenth incarnation of Lord [[Vishnu]] according to the [[dashavatara]].{{citation needed|date=November 2016}} The verse \"Om Shri Anant Hari Naaraaya\u00f1\" is typically invoked as the initiation of a performance, and as the grammatical medium for an [[alap]].{{citation needed|date=January 2019}}\n\n===Specialty ragas and compositions===\nThe Mewati Gharana holds raags unique to its tradition.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Singhji Waghela |first1=Jaiwant |title=Shri Sangeet Saurabh |date=1974 |location=Sanand, Gujarat}}</ref> These include:\n* Raag Jaiwanti Todi: A mixture of raags [[Ahir Bhairav]] and [[Todi (raga)|Todi]], created by Jaiwant Singhji.\n* Raag Jaiwant Sarang: A mixture of raags [[Jaijaiwanti]] and [[Sarang (raga)|Sarang]], created by Jaiwant Singhji.\n* Raag Gyaankali: Inspired by Raag [[Gorakh Kalyan]], created by Jaiwant Singhji.\n* Raag Rajrajeshwari: Created by Jaiwant Singhji.\n* Raag Bagkauns: Created by Jaiwant Singhji.\n* Raag Din Ki Puriya\n* Raag Audav Bageshree\n* Raag Khamaj Bahar\n* Raag Bhavani Bahar\n\n===Haveli Sangeet===\nInformed by the gharana's kirtankar tradition, Jasraj researched the [[haveli sangeet]] of Mathura and Brindavan. Consequently, many devotional compositions have been brought into the gharana's repertoire.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Ray |first1=N. R. |title=Dictionary of National Biography |date=1990 |publisher=Institute of Historical Studies |location=Calcutta |page=173}}</ref>\n\n==Members==\n===Utd. Ghagge Nazir Khan===\n{{Redirect|Ghagge Nazir Khan|other uses|Mewati Gharana}}\n'''\"Ghagge\" Nazir Khan''' (c. 1850 - c. 1920) was born to Imdad Khan, a dhrupadiya, in in the [[Mewat|Mewat region]]. He learned vocal music from Utd. Chote Mohammed Khan (his maternal uncle) and Utd. Waris Ali Khan (his elder brother).<ref>http://www.visualfxindia.com/mewatigharana/html/ghagge_nazir.html</ref> He had no children. He taught music to Pt. Natthhulal, Pt. Chimmanlal, and Utd. Munavvar Khan (his younger brother).\n\n===Utd. Wahid Khan (beenkar)===\n{{Redirect|Wahid Khan (beenkar)|other uses|Mewati Gharana}}\n'''Wahid Khan''' (c. 1840 - 1933) was born to Imdad Khan, a dhrupadiya, in in the [[Mewat|Mewat region]]. He learned [[Rudra Veena|rudra veena]] from [[Bande Ali Khan|Utd. Bande Ali Khan]] (his maternal uncle through marriage).<ref>http://www.visualfxindia.com/mewatigharana/html/wahidkhan.html</ref> Influenced by the Dhrupad ang, Wahid Khan taught instrumental music to his six children who also became musicians.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Music of Haryana]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Mewati gharana| ]]\n[[Category:Vocal gharanas]]\n[[Category:Mewat]]\n[[Category:Rajasthani culture]]\n", "name_user": "Arjayay", "label": "safe", "comment": "Duplicate word removed", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mewati_gharana"}
